WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.320
GraphQL and AppProto are what I sort of came

00:00:06.320 --> 00:00:10.030
to find out what they were comparing two different front-end

00:00:10.030 --> 00:00:12.630
protocols for the social web.

00:00:12.720 --> 00:00:16.590
My background is I was a former social graph developer for eight

00:00:16.670 --> 00:00:17.240
years.

00:00:17.240 --> 00:00:20.410
I designed server-to-client APIs for web,

00:00:20.450 --> 00:00:24.530
cross-platform APIs, working on native code Android and

00:00:24.530 --> 00:00:24.910
iOS.

00:00:24.920 --> 00:00:28.900
I worked on efficiency and latency challenges, building social media U

00:00:28.910 --> 00:00:31.860
Is and real-time data access to apps.

00:00:31.860 --> 00:00:34.990
And I found this tooling so good, it was open source

00:00:34.990 --> 00:00:37.160
and I used it in my own projects.

00:00:37.160 --> 00:00:39.150
So naturally, the first time I came across ATProto

00:00:39.150 --> 00:00:41.340
, I was like, wait, what is the difference between

00:00:41.400 --> 00:00:41.950
these two?

00:00:41.960 --> 00:00:46.580
I just described everything that may be true of ATProto

00:00:46.580 --> 00:00:46.850
.

00:00:46.920 --> 00:00:49.580
So GraphQL is an ubiquitous library, and you don

00:00:49.600 --> 00:00:51.330
't have to take my word for it.

00:00:51.360 --> 00:00:52.640
You just go to GraphQL.

00:00:52.660 --> 00:00:55.760
org and see the number of large companies that are using it

00:00:55.760 --> 00:00:58.460
, like Meta, AWS, GitHub.

00:00:58.460 --> 00:01:00.960
In my world, GraphQL was so ubiquitous that it

00:01:00.970 --> 00:01:04.140
was sort of obvious that at least someone out there would be

00:01:04.140 --> 00:01:07.340
trying to make a comparison of the two technologies, given how

00:01:07.340 --> 00:01:10.400
you could just pop open a web browser, a web dev

00:01:10.400 --> 00:01:14.770
console, and sort of see the truth that most websites are

00:01:14.920 --> 00:01:17.090
using it.

00:01:17.100 --> 00:01:19.730
One major social media website is not listed in that previous list

00:01:19.730 --> 00:01:23.180
, maybe because their CEO doesn't understand how GraphQL works

00:01:23.180 --> 00:01:23.420
.

00:01:23.420 --> 00:01:24.660
Let's not make that mistake today.

00:01:24.660 --> 00:01:26.580
Let's find out.

00:01:26.580 --> 00:01:28.440
So first, when I was looking at this problem, I

00:01:28.440 --> 00:01:30.420
was like, all right, well, I'll search Graph

00:01:30.530 --> 00:01:31.650
QL and at Proto Bridge.

00:01:31.660 --> 00:01:33.560
Surely someone will have documented this.

00:01:33.560 --> 00:01:36.700
And no, every single one of these results is someone not

00:01:36.720 --> 00:01:39.490
answering that question or a mismatch.

00:01:39.620 --> 00:01:42.390
The AI overview gives a description of what that would be,

00:01:42.420 --> 00:01:43.880
but that is not the answer.

00:01:43.880 --> 00:01:47.090
And unfortunately, now the top answer for this is this talk

00:01:47.130 --> 00:01:49.990
, which means this has to be the canonical answer to that

00:01:49.990 --> 00:01:50.200
.

00:01:50.200 --> 00:01:52.220
So let's try to do a good job.

00:01:52.220 --> 00:01:55.690
I asked you to put on your GraphQL colored glasses as

00:01:55.830 --> 00:01:59.040
I, a GraphQL developer, tries to grapple with

00:01:59.040 --> 00:02:01.760
the atmosphere.

00:02:01.760 --> 00:02:04.290
The source code for a demo if I have time, whatever

00:02:04.290 --> 00:02:07.310
, will be available at the bottom of this for the rest

00:02:07.310 --> 00:02:08.600
of the talk.

00:02:08.640 --> 00:02:10.000
So I'd like an intro to what GraphQL is if

00:02:10.020 --> 00:02:10.900
you're not familiar.

00:02:10.900 --> 00:02:12.420
So there's a website, GraphQL.

00:02:12.420 --> 00:02:14.640
org, there's an open source spec, and there's

00:02:14.640 --> 00:02:18.020
a foundation which many companies have joined to work on it.

00:02:18.020 --> 00:02:21.490
It was built by Meta in 2012 to address resource constraints

00:02:21.630 --> 00:02:25.350
on their mobile applications, open source in 2015, and the

00:02:25.350 --> 00:02:28.020
foundation was launched in 2019.

00:02:28.020 --> 00:02:29.910
You can see some things which are very similar to AT Pr

00:02:29.910 --> 00:02:32.340
oto, schema definition language, it wraps REST, much

00:02:32.340 --> 00:02:34.520
like XRPC, and there's types of schemas

00:02:34.540 --> 00:02:35.640
, like Lexicon.

00:02:35.640 --> 00:02:39.040
Maybe two differences, it controls how much data is fetched

00:02:39.040 --> 00:02:42.240
, and ways to fetch data recursively, which I'll

00:02:42.240 --> 00:02:43.560
talk about.

00:02:43.560 --> 00:02:45.960
First is the GraphQL schema language.

00:02:45.960 --> 00:02:48.570
Here I've modeled a conference, an attendee, and

00:02:48.570 --> 00:02:49.360
a location.

00:02:49.360 --> 00:02:51.220
You can see that it's very human readable.

00:02:51.220 --> 00:02:54.350
It was designed for front-end and back-end collaboration

00:02:54.350 --> 00:02:54.600
.

00:02:54.600 --> 00:02:57.080
It supports objects, interfaces, unions.

00:02:57.080 --> 00:03:00.550
Each field, individually, can accept arguments in return, scal

00:03:00.760 --> 00:03:03.910
ars, or other types, and other fields can accept arguments

00:03:03.920 --> 00:03:04.470
as well.

00:03:04.480 --> 00:03:08.480
I think this is the difference between AT Proto and Graph

00:03:08.480 --> 00:03:08.890
QL.

00:03:08.980 --> 00:03:11.140
Like Lexicon, it's forward compatible.

00:03:11.140 --> 00:03:13.490
Unlike Lexicon, you don't need to query all of

00:03:13.490 --> 00:03:14.300
the fields.

00:03:14.300 --> 00:03:16.790
So, you know, you could define a monolithic object

00:03:16.790 --> 00:03:19.190
like this, and you could only list the ID and the

00:03:19.190 --> 00:03:21.890
name, and you'll just get the ID and the name

00:03:21.890 --> 00:03:22.070
.

00:03:22.200 --> 00:03:23.210
Let's talk about querying.

00:03:23.360 --> 00:03:25.630
So here's an example of querying all the Star Wars

00:03:25.630 --> 00:03:26.140
films.

00:03:26.140 --> 00:03:27.130
The first three.

00:03:27.140 --> 00:03:29.020
It will return a list of film objects, and all we

00:03:29.020 --> 00:03:30.610
're going to do is pick up the title.

00:03:30.640 --> 00:03:33.140
Not the ratings, not everyone's opinions about them, but

00:03:33.140 --> 00:03:35.530
just return what's on the right.

00:03:35.640 --> 00:03:38.030
And GraphQL's query DSL has this nice property where

00:03:38.030 --> 00:03:40.710
it kind of looks like the JSON on the right.

00:03:40.720 --> 00:03:41.640
So people really love that in live demos.

00:03:41.640 --> 00:03:44.660
And then we could go and we could add another block here

00:03:44.670 --> 00:03:44.940
.

00:03:44.940 --> 00:03:46.510
Not only do I have the films, I want to add

00:03:46.630 --> 00:03:49.300
like, oh, I want to get the first three characters

00:03:49.300 --> 00:03:52.740
from each of the films, and the response will update accordingly

00:03:52.740 --> 00:03:52.770
.

00:03:52.980 --> 00:03:55.250
One of the nice things about this in GraphQL world is

00:03:55.250 --> 00:03:57.600
that, like, when you select an object and then you

00:03:57.600 --> 00:03:59.700
select subfields on it, you're doing this within

00:03:59.700 --> 00:04:00.570
the same request.

00:04:00.640 --> 00:04:02.660
I think in ATproto, you make it like a

00:04:02.680 --> 00:04:05.480
ref, and then you have to go resolve that ref with

00:04:05.480 --> 00:04:07.380
another network call.

00:04:07.380 --> 00:04:09.320
It's all resolved for you, and there's, depending

00:04:09.330 --> 00:04:11.130
on how your back end is designed, this could be more

00:04:11.290 --> 00:04:14.010
efficient because you're basically doing a SQL join, not just

00:04:14.050 --> 00:04:16.140
two separate SQL calls.

00:04:16.140 --> 00:04:17.130
Okay.

00:04:17.140 --> 00:04:18.130
The ATproto comparison.

00:04:18.140 --> 00:04:19.800
I'm going to make an XRPC, and I

00:04:19.930 --> 00:04:23.180
'm going to get an object which eventually wraps a post,

00:04:23.180 --> 00:04:24.320
let's say.

00:04:24.320 --> 00:04:28.160
Now, this definition is-- sorry, I want to spend

00:04:28.270 --> 00:04:30.600
the next thing-- yeah, so this definition is interesting because

00:04:30.700 --> 00:04:33.070
the post is sort of like the canonical DB format, and

00:04:33.280 --> 00:04:37.350
there are a pattern in Blue Sky where you actually fork that

00:04:37.350 --> 00:04:39.160
and create a post view.

00:04:39.320 --> 00:04:42.060
This is the thing stripped of, like, its like counts

00:04:42.090 --> 00:04:45.000
and follower counts, like counts, reply counts, and everything

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:46.980
because it doesn't have that information when you publish it.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:49.500
So you need to create a lexicon view to sort

00:04:49.500 --> 00:04:52.880
of add that information in, and that's muted by the

00:04:52.880 --> 00:04:53.820
app view.

00:04:53.820 --> 00:04:56.140
So this sort of changes it from the GraphQL world where

00:04:56.150 --> 00:04:59.300
the consumer defines what data they're getting to you actually have

00:04:59.410 --> 00:05:01.940
to publish this and have a lexicon-oriented data

00:05:01.940 --> 00:05:05.480
model to show what you want.

00:05:05.480 --> 00:05:06.820
Let's look at the schema comparison.

00:05:06.820 --> 00:05:08.800
So this is an example of a post-defined in Graph

00:05:08.800 --> 00:05:10.290
QL, looks very human-readable.

00:05:10.440 --> 00:05:12.890
Here is an example of a post-defined in lex

00:05:12.890 --> 00:05:13.400
icon.

00:05:13.440 --> 00:05:16.570
It's certainly machine-readable, but I wouldn't

00:05:16.570 --> 00:05:18.330
say it's human-readable.

00:05:18.440 --> 00:05:20.660
Is there really a big difference between the two, though?

00:05:20.660 --> 00:05:22.520
No, I think they're pretty homomorphic, even

00:05:22.520 --> 00:05:24.520
though the one on the right is much simpler, and they

00:05:24.520 --> 00:05:26.280
don't have, like, constraints around strings, etc.

00:05:26.280 --> 00:05:28.440
And part of the reason for that is, like, well

00:05:28.440 --> 00:05:30.690
, yeah, you could go on a bunch of annotations

00:05:30.700 --> 00:05:32.540
on the thing on the right, but really we're just

00:05:32.540 --> 00:05:33.480
talking about data.

00:05:33.500 --> 00:05:35.660
And if data could be homomorphic, that means you

00:05:35.660 --> 00:05:37.900
could bridge the two, which will be the part of the

00:05:37.940 --> 00:05:38.490
talk I end on.

00:05:38.500 --> 00:05:42.890
So I want to consider three scenarios or takeaways for AT dev

00:05:42.890 --> 00:05:43.340
s.

00:05:43.340 --> 00:05:46.420
A is what GraphQL offers that is different from what exists

00:05:46.420 --> 00:05:47.680
in the atmosphere.

00:05:47.680 --> 00:05:50.140
Now, the second -- oh, yeah, and just as

00:05:50.140 --> 00:05:52.500
a top-line summary, it's, like, these

00:05:52.500 --> 00:05:55.240
are the sort of things that I talked about already.

00:05:55.240 --> 00:05:57.500
There's other things that I could get into, like generation

00:05:57.500 --> 00:05:59.940
via server definitions and, like, tooling, a very robust

00:06:00.300 --> 00:06:02.490
ecosystem of tooling that's cropped up over the last decade

00:06:02.500 --> 00:06:03.490
and a half.

00:06:03.500 --> 00:06:05.490
I think a lot of these are just because of the age

00:06:05.490 --> 00:06:08.070
of the protocol, not things that won't actually come to

00:06:08.130 --> 00:06:11.940
the atmosphere, but it's worth considering where developers are coming

00:06:11.940 --> 00:06:14.830
from when you're trying to give them a way to interface

00:06:14.860 --> 00:06:15.480
with AT.

00:06:15.480 --> 00:06:19.300
So question, is GraphQL federated?

00:06:19.300 --> 00:06:23.410
On the largest open source company's website, they actually list

00:06:23.410 --> 00:06:27.880
-- Apollo -- they list that GraphQL has federation.

00:06:27.880 --> 00:06:30.420
But I will actually give you the example of what are first

00:06:30.450 --> 00:06:33.020
-party APIs that you can consume GraphQL with.

00:06:33.020 --> 00:06:34.610
And I went to this page and I kept scrolling and I

00:06:34.810 --> 00:06:36.100
only came away with GitHub, GitLab.

00:06:36.100 --> 00:06:40.100
Shopify and Yelp as examples.

00:06:40.100 --> 00:06:42.880
So, really, it's not federated if there are

00:06:42.900 --> 00:06:45.930
so few first-party implementations that they're willing to

00:06:45.960 --> 00:06:47.240
bank other people accessing.

00:06:47.280 --> 00:06:49.460
And I think the reason for that is the NSID.

00:06:49.480 --> 00:06:52.950
And the NSID means that I can actually publish something --

00:06:52.950 --> 00:06:54.980
let's take the Yelp review API.

00:06:54.980 --> 00:06:58.140
I can publish an object from my API, which is the

00:06:58.140 --> 00:07:01.370
Yelp review API, if they were conforming to that

00:07:01.470 --> 00:07:01.970
schema.

00:07:01.980 --> 00:07:04.140
If they're conforming to GraphQL, you can't

00:07:04.140 --> 00:07:04.400
.

00:07:04.400 --> 00:07:05.390
I'm lying.

00:07:05.400 --> 00:07:06.400
It's not true.

00:07:06.400 --> 00:07:07.390
They could change it at any time.

00:07:07.400 --> 00:07:09.420
They could change it when you have a lossy lex

00:07:09.420 --> 00:07:11.400
icon inside of your own applications.

00:07:11.400 --> 00:07:13.400
But it doesn't accomplish federation.

00:07:13.400 --> 00:07:16.730
And what they mean for federation inside of Apollo is actually

00:07:16.730 --> 00:07:20.520
federation across REST backends, GraphQL backends

00:07:20.520 --> 00:07:21.400
, et cetera.

00:07:21.400 --> 00:07:24.140
Try to take all the different data sources you might have and

00:07:24.140 --> 00:07:25.400
put them into one pipe.

00:07:25.400 --> 00:07:30.520
So, GraphQL's role in existing applications to bridge to

00:07:30.690 --> 00:07:34.190
AppProto might be, a lot of companies are using

00:07:34.190 --> 00:07:34.580
it.

00:07:34.580 --> 00:07:36.580
It consumes a lot of APIs.

00:07:36.580 --> 00:07:39.110
Maybe if we introduce AppProto to those consumers, we

00:07:39.140 --> 00:07:42.170
can get more AppProto connections and integrations into public

00:07:42.170 --> 00:07:42.520
apps.

00:07:42.640 --> 00:07:45.570
I'm going to skip to my pitch about what a new

00:07:45.570 --> 00:07:47.760
application could consider.

00:07:47.840 --> 00:07:49.090
Eight minutes?

00:07:49.120 --> 00:07:50.110
Yeah.

00:07:50.120 --> 00:07:54.380
So, brief pitch for -- I started this by working on

00:07:54.380 --> 00:07:58.240
a Craigslist competitor marketplace-style app, which I

00:07:58.310 --> 00:08:01.210
called Mothball, no relation to Anasota.

00:08:01.300 --> 00:08:02.840
This was the pitch I came in with.

00:08:02.840 --> 00:08:04.540
I was going to build an Expo app and be like

00:08:04.640 --> 00:08:06.800
, "What is it like to build an application with App

00:08:06.810 --> 00:08:10.350
Proto integration?" And I started with a GraphQL,

00:08:10.350 --> 00:08:12.040
a mock GraphQL, and I was going to move it

00:08:12.050 --> 00:08:12.780
to the server.

00:08:12.780 --> 00:08:14.840
And then I learned about AppProto, and now I

00:08:14.840 --> 00:08:16.200
'm down this rabbit hole.

00:08:16.200 --> 00:08:18.600
So I was thinking low latency in mobile and web.

00:08:18.600 --> 00:08:21.640
There's some strategic benefit there with GraphQL.

00:08:21.640 --> 00:08:23.800
You can do sensitive off-proto data, and you

00:08:23.800 --> 00:08:25.160
can wrap non-AT services.

00:08:25.160 --> 00:08:28.990
There's geocarding search indexes, et cetera

00:08:29.110 --> 00:08:31.080
, behind a single API.

00:08:31.080 --> 00:08:33.350
That might be a case for using GraphQL as a front

00:08:33.380 --> 00:08:35.040
-end for AppProto on new apps.

00:08:35.040 --> 00:08:37.820
But I think the best case scenario is actually this middle ground

00:08:37.840 --> 00:08:39.180
where we bridge the two.

00:08:39.180 --> 00:08:41.540
So now I'll stop there for questions, but while I

00:08:41.540 --> 00:08:43.180
show this demo really quick.

00:08:43.180 --> 00:08:47.040
The demo is just this button.

00:08:47.100 --> 00:08:49.100
So here we go.

00:08:49.100 --> 00:08:53.100
This is the lexicon of XRPC request,

00:08:53.100 --> 00:08:55.030
and on the right, I'm fetching live data from

00:08:55.200 --> 00:08:56.100
the atmosphere.

00:08:56.100 --> 00:08:58.990
Here's an example of doing multiple XRPCs in

00:08:58.990 --> 00:09:02.030
the same call from feed and from your actor.

00:09:02.100 --> 00:09:03.930
Go check out my repo if you want to play around more

00:09:03.930 --> 00:09:05.060
with this code generation.

00:09:05.100 --> 00:09:07.100
Thanks very much.

00:09:07.100 --> 00:09:09.460
Thank you, Tim.
